// TEST: exec_iter_manual_drive
// EXPECT: output "sum=6"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// End-to-end proof that the embedded `core.iter` `ListIterator` drives the
// proven manual loop: `list_iter([1, 2, 3])` builds a `ListIterator[Int]`, and
// `loop { match it.next() { Some(x) => ...; None => break } }` sums its
// elements. This is the SAME drive shape as the hand-written
// `generic_iter_concrete_match.bock` (#149), here resolved through the embedded
// `core.iter` module.
//
// TARGETS — all five. The embedded `core.iter` module compiles ALL its items
// into every importing program (no tree-shaking), so even this manual-drive
// program that never calls a combinator pulls in the whole module and must
// compile on the target. The generic combinator/constructor codegen residue on
// Rust and Go (Rust `T: Clone` propagation to combinator free fns; Go
// generic-record-construct, concat-arg typed list literals, the `Iterable[T]`
// interface header, and lambda arg-type specialisation) is fixed in the
// rust/go codegen fast-follow, so rust/go now compile and run alongside
// js/ts/python.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

use core.iter.{ListIterator, list_iter}

fn main() -> Void {
  let mut it: ListIterator[Int] = list_iter([1, 2, 3])
  let mut total: Int = 0
  loop {
    match it.next() {
      Some(x) => {
        total = total + x
      }
      None => break
    }
  }
  println("sum=${total}")
}
